def: A variety of pigeon, with a crest somewhat resembling the maneof a horse. [Written also finikin.]
To frame; to devise; to disguise or excuse; hence, to pretend;to declare falsely. [Obs.]
Pertaining to, or designating, an acid which is obtained fromgallic acid as a brown or red crystalline substance, and is relatedto rufiopin and anthracene.
To curl or friz, as the hair. [Obs.] Cotgrave.
The person at whose suit an arrestment is made. [Also writtenarrestor.]
Inclined to eat; hungry; voracious. [R.] Bailey. "Poor, butesurient." Carlyle.
Of, pertaining to, or designating, an organic acid, obtainedindirectly from mucic acid, and somewhat resembling itaconic acid.
The quality or state of being omniscient; -- an attributepeculiar to God. Dryden.

The goddess of retribution or vengeance; hence, retributivejustice personified; divine vengeance.This is that ancient doctrine of nemesis who keeps watch in theuniverse, and lets no offense go unchastised. Emerson.
Full to the top, ore brim; brimfull. "Topful of direstcruelty." Shak.[He] was so topful of himself, that he let it spill on all thecompany. I. Watts.
Pertaining to, consisting of, or resembling, flame. [Obs.] SirT. Browne.
